2. Choosing the best model (1pt each, 7 pts total)

For each of the following scenarios, decide what random variable may be appropriate to use as a model, and explain your reasoning as well as any assumptions you make.

  1. The number of patients in an experimental drug trial that respond to treatment. > binomial random variable. We are measuging the number of sucesses in a fixed number of trials. I am assuming we are not measuring this in a fixed interval of time so it is not a poisson distribution, and I am assuming we are going to have more than 1 trial in this experiment, meaning it is not a bernouli distribution.

  2. The number of red cars you observe driving through an intersection between 10am and 11am. > Poisson random variable. Since we are observing the number of sucesses in a fixed interval of time, it could not be any other distribution. I am assuming that the red car observanbces are independent of each other and there i snot a red car convention occuring nearby.

  3. What the second hand reads on the clock when you wake up (without an alarm clock) from a long nap (approximately). > descrete uniform random variable. assuming that you could be starting this nap at any time of the day at any level of sleepiness, we can say that the distribution of wake up times for this type of nap is uniformly distributed.

  4. How many people you need to swipe right on Tinder before you get a match. > geometric random variable. Since the last swipe in order to get the match requires for you to swipe, we are also counting this sucess as a trial and therefore we are not measuring the number of failures until the first sucess, which is why this is a geometric random variable.

  5. The length of time between mosquito bites a camper experiences while on a hike. > exponential rtandom variable. Assuming we are measuring the interval of time between mosquito bites, and the number of mosquito bites in a given amouint of time follows the poisson distribution, the waiting time between them is exponential.

  6. Whether the Eagles win the Superbowl this year. > bernoili random variable. this is because we are measuring a binbomial variable with just one trial, as the Eagles cannot win multiple times at the superbowl in one year. We are assuming that the probability of sucess is constant for this one trial that we are taking.

  7. The GPA of a randomly selected UW-Madison graduate. > normal random variable. I am assuming that grade curves are all normally distributed for all classes, and therfore, the distribution of GPAs for uw madison students can be modeled with a normal distribution.

.9^7

4. Correlated Normal Random Variables (2pts each, 10pts total)

Let \(X\) and \(Y\) be normally distributed random variables with \(\mu_X=50\) and \(\mu_Y=30\). Their covariance matrix given by \[\Sigma = \left[\begin{matrix}100 & 75\\75 & 225\end{matrix}\right]\] In other words, \(\sigma^2_X=10^2\), \(\sigma^2_Y=15^2\) and \(\rho_{XY}=.5\)

  1. Using the rules of combining random variables, find the distribution of \(X+Y\). (hint: the sum of two normally distributed random variables will also follow a normal distribution) > X ~ norm(mu = 80, sigma^2 = 475)

  2. Calculate \(Pr[60 < X+Y < 90]\)

pnorm(90, mean = 80, sd = sqrt(475)) - pnorm(60, mean = 80, sd = sqrt(475))
## [1] 0.4974247

.497

To simulate values from this distribution we can use the mvrnorm function in the MASS package. The following code will generate a dataframe with 10000 samples from this distribution.

library(MASS)
mu <- c(50,30)
Sigma <- matrix(c(100,75,75,225), byrow=T, nrow=2)
XYdata <- mvrnorm(10000, mu, Sigma)
colnames(XYdata) <- c("X","Y")
XYdata <- as.data.frame(XYdata)
# un-comment the next line to plot the data
ggplot(XYdata) + geom_point(aes(x=X, y=Y), pch=1)

  1. Create a new column W that is X+Y. Using the values in this column, verify your answer for part a. using a histogram and calculating the mean and variance of \(W\).
XYdata$W <- XYdata$X + XYdata$Y

mean(XYdata$W)
## [1] 79.97285
var(XYdata$W)
## [1] 467.6799
hist(XYdata$W, 
     main = "Histogram for W = X+Y", 
     xlab = "W", 
     breaks = 50, )

  1. Using the values in W, verify your answer for part b. > looks close enough, maybe some rounding difference

  2. Using your simulated data, approximate an answer to \(Pr(Y > 50 | X > 65)\).

5. The Geometric, The Poisson and the Exponential (2pts each, 14pts total)

In this problem we’ll explore the relationship between three random variable distributions.

Suppose we’re modeling an experiment where photons hit a glass plate. The average rate of collision is 90/second.

  1. What is the probability that 100 or fewer photons hit the plate in one hour?
ppois(100, 3600*90)
## [1] 0

virtually 0

  1. What is the probability that it takes .03 or fewer seconds for the next photon to hit?
pexp(0.03, rate = 90)
## [1] 0.9327945

.933

  1. What is the probability that it takes .001 milliseconds or fewer for the first collision?
pexp(.001/1000, rate = 90)
## [1] 8.999595e-05

8.999595e-05

The following code will simulate the times between collisions in seconds.

collision.s <- rexp(10000, 90)

Suppose we are counting collisions per second. The following code will count how many collisions occur during each second of the experiment.

collision.count <- as.vector(table(floor(cumsum(collision.s))))
  1. Plot a histogram of the collision.count. What is the mean number of collisions per second? In theory what should the distribution of collision.count be?
count_df <- data.frame(counts = collision.count)

# Plot the histogram using ggplot
ggplot(count_df, aes(x = counts)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Collisions per Second",
       x = "Number of Collisions",
       y = "Frequency")

mean(collision.count)
## [1] 89.28571

90.09

Suppose we were to round to the nearest millisecond - to convert seconds to millseconds, multiply by 1000, and round to the nearest integer. In this sense, we could consider the data recorded as “counting how many milliseconds before the next collision”.

  1. Convert to milliseconds and save this vector as collision.ms. Plot a histogram of the milliseconds, and calculate the mean and variance. If you were to model the collision time (ms) as a geometric random variable, what parameter \(p\) would you use? (hint: the expected value of a geometric rv is \(1/p-1\).)

6. Random Variables in a Coffee Shop (1pt each, 8pts total)

A small coffee shop records the number of customers arriving each morning between 8–9 a.m. They have noticed that:

  • On average, 12 customers arrive in that hour. The arrivals can be modeled as a Poisson random variable.

  • Each customer spends, on average, $4.50 with a standard deviation of $2.00. The spending per customer is independent and approximately follows a Normal distribution.

Let \(X\) be the number of customers who arrive between 8–9 a.m.

  1. Write down the distribution of \(X\). > X ~ pois(l;ambda = 12)

  2. What is the probability that exactly 10 customers arrive in an hour?

dpois(10, lambda = 12)
## [1] 0.1048373

.105

  1. What is the probability that at least 15 customers arrive in an hour?
ppois(14, lambda = 12, lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 0.2279755

.228

Let \(Y\) be the spending of a single customer.

  1. State the distribution of \(Y\). > Y ~ normal(mu 4.5, sigma^2 = 4)

  2. What is the probability a single customer spends more than $6?

pnorm(6, mean = 4.5, sd = 2, lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 0.2266274

.227

Now let \(Z\) be the total revenue between 8–9 a.m.

  1. What is the expected value of \(Z\)?
12*4.5
## [1] 54

$54

  1. What is the variance of \(Z\)? (hint: \(Z\) is a random sum: \(Z=\sum_{i=1}^X Y_i\). The Variance of a random sum is \(Var(Z)=EX\cdot VarY + VarX + E^2Y\))
48 + (12*20.25)
## [1] 291

291
